04404nam a22007335i 9780691184593DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911845937 a10.1515/97806911845932doi  a(DE-B1597)501740  a(OCoLC)1076442376  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aE302 7aBIO0110002bisacsh 7aHIS0360302bisacsh04a973.460922211 aJefferson, Thomas, eauthor.10aPapers of Thomas Jefferson - Retirement Series. pThe Papers of Thomas Jefferson, Retirement Series, Volume 1 ; 4 March 1809 to 15 November 1809 /cThomas Jefferson; J. Jefferson Looney. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4c©2005  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPapers of Thomas Jefferson - Retirement Series00tFrontmatter -- tINTRODUCTION -- tFOREWORD -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tEDITORIAL METHOD AND APPARATUS -- tCONTENTS -- tMAPS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tJEFFERSON CHRONOLOGY 1743 • 1826 -- tRETIREMENT -- tMARCH 1809 -- tAPRIL 1809 -- tMAY 1809 -- tJUNE 1809 -- tJULY 1809 -- tAUGUST 1809 -- tSEPTEMBER 1809 -- tOCTOBER 1809 -- tNOVEMBER 1809 -- tAppendix -- tINDEX  aThis volume inaugurates the definitive edition of papers from Thomas Jefferson's retirement. As the volume opens, a new president is installed and Jefferson is anticipating his return to Virginia, where he will pursue a fascinating range of personal and intellectual activities. He prepares for his final departure from Washington by settling accounts and borrowing to pay his creditors. At Monticello he tells of his efforts to restore order at his mismanaged mill complex, breed merino sheep, and otherwise resume full control of his financial and agricultural affairs. Though he is entering retirement, he still has one foot firmly planted in the world of public affairs. He acknowledges a flood of accolades on his retirement and has frequent exchanges with President James Madison. While fielding written requests for money, favors, and advice from a kaleidoscopic array of relatives, acquaintances, strangers, cranks, anonymous writers, and a blackmailer, he maintains a wide and varied correspondence with scientists and scholars on both sides of the Atlantic. The volume's highlights include first-hand accounts of Jefferson's demeanor at his successor's inauguration and one of the most detailed descriptions of life at Monticello by a visitor; Jefferson's recommendations on book purchases to a literary club and a teacher; chemical analyses of tobacco by a French scientist that first isolated nicotine; the earliest descriptions of the death of Meriwether Lewis; one of Jefferson's most eloquent calls for religious tolerance; and his modest assessment of the value of his writings in reply to a printer interested in publishing them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aPresidentszUnited StatesvArchives. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesvCorrespondence. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Presidents & Heads of State.2bisacsh1 aLooney, J. Jefferson, eeditor.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691184593zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691184593.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN